======================================================================
Beneshesh: A FIXED-MATRIX BENESH COORDINATE SPECIFICATION (v1.0)
======================================================================

1. SPATIAL ARCHITECTURE
-----------------------
A single "Beat" or "Moment" is a 5x11 character matrix. 
- Y-Axis (Vertical): 5 lines representing the BMN Staff levels.
- X-Axis (Horizontal): 11 columns representing the Coronal Plane.
- Center Column [6]: The Spine/Midline.

2. THE 5-LINE HEIGHT MAP (Y-AXIS)
---------------------------------
Line 1: TOP    [Head/Crown]
Line 2: UPPER  [Shoulders/Elbows]
Line 3: MIDDLE [Waist/Hands at rest]
Line 4: LOWER  [Knees]
Line 5: BASE   [Feet/Floor]

3. THE DEPTH ENCODING (Z-AXIS)
------------------------------
The primary character in any cell defines its relationship to the plane.
- [ - ] LEVEL  : On the body plane.
- [ o ] FRONT  : In front of the body.
- [ | ] BEHIND : Behind the body.
- [ + ] CROSS  : Crossing the midline (X-coordinate shift).

4. NUANCE & ARTICULATION LAYER (The "Modifier")
-----------------------------------------------
Each coordinate can be modified to show joint state or orientation.
In a data-stream, these are appended to the depth marker or 
separated into a secondary "Nuance Grid."

A. JOINT STATE (Flexion)
- [ \ ] or [ / ] : Tick (Joint flexed).
- [ v ] : Deep contraction/fold.
- [ ! ] : Hyper-extension/Rigid tension.

B. ORIENTATION (Facing)
- [ < ] : Palm/Face oriented Left.
- [ > ] : Palm/Face oriented Right.
- [ ^ ] : Oriented Up/Open.
- [ u ] : Oriented Down/Grounded.

C. WEIGHT & CONTACT
- [ # ] : Weight-bearing (Support).
- [ @ ] : Contact (Touching another body part or object).

5. THE MATRIX BLOCK (EXAMPLE)
-----------------------------
A dancer in a deep pli√©, arms folded in front of the chest.

BEAT 01
(L1)  . . . . . - . . . . .  // Head level
(L2)  . . o v . . . o v . .  // Elbows flexed in front
(L3)  . . . . . . . . . . .  // Hands (implied at L2)
(L4)  . . . \ . . . / . . .  // Knees bent (Level)
(L5)  . . # . . . . . # . .  // Feet supporting weight



6. STRING SERIALIZATION (One-to-One Flat Code)
----------------------------------------------
For computational analysis, the 55-cell matrix is flattened into 
a single string, read left-to-right, top-to-bottom.

Format: [L1_String][L2_String][L3_String][L4_String][L5_String]

A "Neutral Stand" would serialize as:
".....-..........-.........................-.....-.."

7. CONVERTER RULES FOR ABSTRACTION
----------------------------------
- TRANSPOSE: To flip the movement, mirror the index around Column 6.
- TIME-STRETCH: Repeat the matrix block N times to extend duration.
- INTERPOLATION: Moving from Matrix A to Matrix B creates a 
  mathematical vector for the "Path."
======================================================================
